  yield original-output ≡ "Cats purr through a rhythmic vibration of the laryngeal muscles at 25-150 Hz, controlled by a neural oscillator in the brain. Evolutionarily, purring serves multiple functions including self-healing (the frequencies promote bone density and tissue repair), communication with kittens, and solicitation of care from humans. Cats purr in diverse contexts — contentment, stress, injury, and social bonding — suggesting it is a versatile self-soothing and signaling mechanism."

